{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# S7 — End-to-end proof + backup/restore drill + monitoring + runbooks\n\n## Why\nProve the whole gate works end-to-end and that freeze-and-restore is real. This is the\ndogfood-readiness checkpoint for d251 (P1 integrity proven on a real change; P3 restore\nproven). The full four-pass dogfood is b744-WS6.\n\n## What\n- **E2E proof:** push a change -> the bot reviews + votes `LLM-Review` -> submit\n  (whole-topic) -> replicate -> the change appears on GitHub `main`; AND a direct GitHub\n  push / PR-merge to `main` is rejected.\n  - **`LLM-Review` label-integer vocabulary (so the e2e test can assert a concrete value).**\n    The MCP voter maps the review kernel's `pass3_decide` outcomes\n    (`{block, advisory, dropped, indeterminate}`, see `src/rebar/llm/review_kernel/decide.py`)\n    to the `LLM-Review` Gerrit label. The e2e test asserts the integer for a *passing*\n    change. The mapping the test must assume: a passing review votes **MAX** (the value\n    `label:LLM-Review=MAX` resolves to in d251's `project.config` label range — the e2e\n    test reads the achieved label value from Gerrit and asserts it equals that range's MAX,\n    rather than hardcoding `+1` vs `+2`); `block` votes the label's MIN (Gerrit refuses\n    submit); `advisory`/`dropped` cast no blocking vote (do not satisfy the submit\n    requirement); `indeterminate` is **fail-closed** (treated as not-passing, no submit).\n    The exact integers are pinned by d251's `project.config` label definition — this AC\n    cross-references that, so the e2e test and the project config agree on MAX/MIN by\n    construction rather than by a guessed literal.\n  - **Indeterminate / no-vote fallback (e2e harness robustness).** The e2e test script must\n    bound the wait for the `LLM-Review` vote with an explicit timeout and must distinguish\n    three terminal states: (a) **MAX vote + submit succeeds** = pass; (b) **block/MIN vote**\n    or an explicit fail-closed `indeterminate` = \"gate correctly blocked\" (expected only in\n    the negative-path sub-test, a failure in the positive path); (c) **no vote within the\n    timeout** = \"voter/harness failed\" — surfaced as a distinct, non-ambiguous harness error,\n    NOT silently conflated with a correctly-blocked change. This makes a model\n    outage/timeout during the drill diagnosable rather than a hang.\n- **Backup/restore:** verify DLM snapshots + a `$site_path` snapshot (git/ + etc/ incl.\n  secure.config + ssh_host keys; index/ + cache/ excluded, taken from a snapshot/stop window,\n  not a naive hot tar); run a restore-from-IaC drill and record the achieved RTO; confirm\n  merged code is safe on GitHub (RPO = only in-flight reviews at risk).\n  - **RTO target (pre-stated, not circular).** A numeric **RTO target of ≤ 2 hours** is the\n    pass/fail bound, agreed *before* the drill and documented in the restore runbook. The\n    drill records the *achieved* RTO and passes only if it is within that 2-hour target\n    (the target is the baseline; the achieved time is measured against it). 2 h is the\n    starting target for this single-instance, IaC-rebuild + `$site_path`-restore topology;\n    the runbook may revise it for a later drill, but a drill never sets its own target.\n  - **Snapshot retention.** The DLM lifecycle policy carries a bounded retention\n    (`retain_rule { count = N }`, default **N = 7**) and the `$site_path` snapshots carry an\n    equivalent TTL/count so snapshots do not accumulate unbounded; the restore runbook states\n    how to identify the latest valid snapshot for a drill.\n  - **Restore-drill safety against production state.** The Terraform resource(s) for the\n    stateful Gerrit data layer (the EBS data volume, and/or the instance with its attached\n    volume) carry `lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true }` so a `terraform apply` during the\n    restore drill cannot destroy the data volume before the `$site_path` restore. The runbook\n    documents that any intentional replacement requires explicitly removing `prevent_destroy`\n    under a plan review, and that the drill snapshots/detaches the old volume before any\n    volume-replacement step.\n- **Monitoring:** CloudWatch basic + an alarm on \"gate down\" (Gerrit/MCP unreachable) so an\n  outage — which freezes `main` — is noticed.\n  - **Probe mechanism (resolves the no-ALB / plain-EC2 gap).** Because d251 excludes an ALB,\n    CloudWatch has no native HTTP-reachability metric for the on-box services. The plan pins\n    one concrete mechanism: a **cron/systemd-timer health probe on the EC2 host** runs every\n    60 s, curls Gerrit (`curl -sf http://localhost:8080/config/server/version`) and the MCP\n    health endpoint, and publishes a binary custom metric via\n    `aws cloudwatch put-metric-data --namespace Rebar/Gate --metric-name GerritReachable\n    --value 1|0`. The `aws_cloudwatch_metric_alarm` in `monitoring.tf` fires when\n    `GerritReachable < 1` for **2 consecutive 60 s periods**. This detects process/port-level\n    gate-down (not just EC2 `StatusCheckFailed`, which would miss a Gerrit/MCP crash). The\n    probe script and the metric namespace/name are the explicit interface contract documented\n    in the monitoring runbook so a Gerrit upgrade that moves the health path is a known,\n    versioned change point.\n  - **Notification delivery (so an outage is actually noticed).** The alarm's `alarm_actions`\n    point at an **SNS topic** whose subscription endpoint is the team alert target\n    (email/Slack/PagerDuty). The endpoint is stored in **SSM Parameter Store** (consistent\n    with d251's secrets-at-boot pattern) and read via `data.aws_ssm_parameter` in\n    `monitoring.tf` — not committed as a plaintext `.tfvars` value. An alarm with empty\n    `alarm_actions` does not satisfy this story.\n  - **IAM scope.** Enumerate the minimum IAM actions the new resources need — CloudWatch\n    (`PutMetricAlarm`/`PutMetricData`/`DescribeAlarms`), DLM (the snapshot lifecycle role with\n    `ec2:CreateSnapshot`/`ec2:DescribeVolumes` scoped to the data volume), SNS\n    (`CreateTopic`/`Publish`) — scoped to the specific resources (no `cloudwatch:*`/`dlm:*`\n    wildcards), added to the existing instance profile or a dedicated scoped DLM role.\n- **Terraform state.** `infra/terraform/monitoring.tf` uses the **shared remote backend**\n  established by the earlier infra stories (S3 state + DynamoDB locking, `us-east-1`), not\n  local state, so concurrent applies during a drill cannot corrupt state; the runbook makes\n  `terraform plan` (reviewed) a required step before `apply`.\n- **Runbooks:** provision/restore + the one-minor-at-a-time Gerrit upgrade.\n- **Sequencing (de-risk order).** Execute E2E proof first (validates the live gate) ->\n  monitoring alarm (observability of that gate) -> restore drill (recoverability) ->\n  runbooks (document the above); each step is evidence-gated on the previous.\n\n## Scope\nIn: the e2e proof, the restore drill, monitoring, runbooks. Out: the full four-pass\ndogfood (b744-WS6); choosing the *final* alarm threshold/period tuning and the *final*\nRTO target beyond the stated starting values (operational tuning, left to the implementer\nwithin the mechanism/bounds fixed here).\n\n## Files\n- `infra/runbooks/*.md` — provision/restore runbook (includes RTO target, snapshot\n  identification, `prevent_destroy` handling, `terraform plan`-before-`apply`) and the\n  one-minor-at-a-time Gerrit upgrade runbook (documents the probe health-endpoint contract).\n- `infra/terraform/monitoring.tf` — CloudWatch alarm (`GerritReachable < 1` for 2 periods)\n  + SNS topic/subscription (endpoint from SSM) + DLM snapshot lifecycle policy\n  (`retain_rule.count = 7`) + scoped IAM; uses the shared S3+DynamoDB backend; adds/asserts\n  `lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true }` on the stateful data-volume resource.\n- The host health-probe script (cron/systemd timer) publishing the `Rebar/Gate/GerritReachable`\n  custom metric (co-located with the host provisioning assets).\n- An e2e test script under `infra/tests/` (push->review->vote->submit->replicate assertion,\n  the negative-path GitHub-direct-push-rejected assertion, the `LLM-Review`=MAX label-value\n  assertion read against `project.config`, and the timeout/terminal-state fallback logic).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] E2E proof passes: a test change is reviewed + voted + submitted in Gerrit and appears on\n      GitHub `main`; the e2e test asserts the cast `LLM-Review` value equals the label range's\n      MAX (as defined in d251 `project.config`); a direct GitHub push / PR-merge to `main` is\n      rejected. The test bounds the vote wait with a timeout and reports \"no vote / harness\n      failure\" distinctly from \"gate correctly blocked.\"\n- [ ] A restore-from-backup drill succeeds (rebuild from Terraform + restore `$site_path`)\n      within the **pre-stated ≤ 2-hour RTO target**, and the achieved RTO is recorded; the\n      restored snapshot is confirmed to exclude `index/` and `cache/` and to have been taken\n      from a quiesced stop/freeze window (not a live hot tar); merged history is confirmed\n      intact on GitHub. The stateful data-volume Terraform resource carries\n      `lifecycle { prevent_destroy = true }`.\n- [ ] A gate-down condition raises an alert: the host probe publishes the\n      `Rebar/Gate/GerritReachable` custom metric, and the CloudWatch alarm fires\n      (`GerritReachable < 1` for 2 consecutive periods) and delivers a notification via its\n      SNS topic to the configured (SSM-sourced) endpoint — `alarm_actions` is non-empty and a\n      simulated gate-down delivers an actual notification.\n- [ ] A DLM/`$site_path` snapshot retention policy is in effect (DLM `retain_rule.count`\n      bounded; default 7) so snapshots do not accumulate unbounded, and IAM for the new\n      monitoring/DLM/SNS resources is scoped to specific resources (no wildcard actions).\n- [ ] Provision/restore + Gerrit upgrade runbooks exist under `infra/runbooks/`, documenting\n      the RTO target, snapshot identification, the probe health-endpoint contract, the\n      `prevent_destroy` removal procedure, and `terraform plan`-before-`apply` on the shared\n      remote backend."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782689176394290001,"uuid":"b5d99aa3-ff9d-4ba4-9e62-574d71f2f507"}